]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The DTS follows the ISO 23247 reference architecture adapted for automotive use: a three‑entity constellation (Physical Twin, Digital Twin, User) with functional entities implemented as ROS 2 packages. Intra‑entity communication uses ROS 2 topics/services; inter‑entity communication uses UDP over Wi‑Fi. The Data Translation FE serializes, aligns, and unit‑converts all streams. Computation offloading moves the ACC control logic to a cloud resource, while actuation remains on the physical vehicle. Resource management is realized by mapping each functional entity to dedicated ROS 2 nodes running on the appropriate hardware component."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The system uses a hybrid network architecture. Within each entity (Physical Twin, Digital Twin, User) software components are packaged as ROS 2 nodes and communicate via a ROS 2 DDS‑based network. Inter‑entity communication (e.g., between Physical Twin Entity and Digital Twin Entity) is carried out over a Wi‑Fi network using UDP at the transport layer. The DT must support low end‑to‑end latency to satisfy ACC requirements, and clock synchronization between devices is required with an accuracy of 100 ms (limited by hardware). No explicit bandwidth, redundancy, or security protocol (e.g., TLS) is mentioned in the documents."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin services are implemented as ROS 2 packages that can be deployed on external compute resources; the paper refers to off‑loading the ACC computation to the DT, suggesting cloud or edge execution, though the exact hosting platform is not detailed. Data collected (object tracks, vehicle state) are stored in an external SQL database (Data Storage FE). Computational requirements include the ACC Controlling FE, point‑cloud processing, and visualization, but quantitative CPU, memory or storage specifications are not provided. Scalability mechanisms, deployment models (cloud, edge, on‑premise) and availability/redundancy strategies are not described in the supplied material."
